The '''Ten Major Construction Projects''' ({{zh|t=十大建設|p=Shí Dà jiànshè}}) were the national infrastructure projects during the 1970s in [[Taiwan]]. The government of Republic of China believed that the country lacked key utilities such as highways, seaports, airports and power plants. Moreover, Taiwan was experiencing significant effects from the [[1973 oil crisis]]. Therefore, to upgrade the industry and the development of the country, the government planned to take on ten massive building projects. They were proposed by the [[Premier of the Republic of China|Premier]] [[Chiang Ching-kuo]], beginning in 1974, with a planned completion by 1979. There were six transportation projects, three industrial projects, and one power-plant construction project, which ultimately cost over [[New Taiwan dollar|NT$]]300 billion in total.<ref>http://www.moeasmea.gov.tw/ct.asp?xItem=72&CtNode=263&mp=2</ref>
==The Ten Projects== # North-South Freeway ([[Freeway 1 (Taiwan)|National Highway No. 1]]) # [[Railway electrification system|Electrification]] of [[West Coast line (Taiwan)|West Coast Line]] railway # [[North-Link Line]] railway # [[Taoyuan International Airport|Chiang Kai-shek International Airport]] (later renamed Taoyuan International Airport) # [[Port of Taichung|Taichung Port]] # [[Su'ao|Su-ao]] Port # Large [[Shipyard]] ([[Kaohsiung]] Shipyard of [[China Shipbuilding Corporation]]) # Integrated [[steel mill]] ([[China Steel|China Steel Corporation]]) # [[Oil refinery]] and [[industrial park]] (Kaohsiung refinery of [[CPC Corporation]] ) # [[Nuclear power plant]] ([[Jinshan Nuclear Power Plant]])
==See also== * [[New Ten Major Construction Projects]] * [[History of Republic of China]]
